  "answer": "The corpus does not contain a chapter explicitly titled 'Tarana-e-Hindi' in Bang-e-Dara Part 1. The closest Part 1 poem that celebrates Hindostan as homeland is 'Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet' (ch. 26, allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c). The contradiction can be staged as follows:\n\n**Part 1, ch. 26 — 'Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet' (celebrating Hindostan):**\n> \"Where Chishti first Truth's holy call conveyed, / And Nanak's song of Oneness was displayed... / This is my homeland, this land of mine.\"\n> \"Its people Moses, and its peaks are Sinai's height... / To live here is a paradise of pure delight, / This is my homeland, this land of mine.\"\n\nHere Iqbal ties identity to a specific territory — the Indian subcontinent — and calls it 'my homeland' (mera watan) with unambiguous devotion.\n\n**Part 3, ch. 25 — 'Wataniyat' (critiquing territorial nationalism):**\n> \"Of all these newer gods, the greatest is the Nation; / The robe it wears is Faith's own final desecration.\"\n> \"This idol, forged by this new age's philosophy, / Lays waste the Prophet's house of faith and piety.\"\n> \"Your homeland is Islam, you serve the Prophet's will.\"\n> \"In the discourse of the state, the Nation is but land; / In the Prophet's teaching, Homeland is by God's command.\"\n> \"By it, God's own creation is in pieces torn, / By it, the roots of Islam's brotherhood are shorn.\"\n\nThe contradiction is sharp: in Part 1 Iqbal sings 'this land of mine' with territorial pride, binding self to soil. In Part 3's Wataniyat he condemns exactly this attachment as idolatry — nationalism is 'the greatest idol,' the 'robe of Faith's final desecration.' The very word 'watan' (homeland) that he used lovingly for Hindustan is redefined: true homeland is Islam, not any piece of land. The early poem's refrain ('this is my homeland') is precisely the sentiment Wataniyat dismantles.",
