**Key finding:** The corpus has no chapter titled "Tarana-e-Hindi" in Part 1. The question's framing points to **"Hindustani Bachon Ka Qaumi Geet"** (Part 1, ch. 26) as the celebratory counterpart — it uses the refrain "This is my homeland, this land of mine" (mera watan wohi hai) to anchor identity in Indian soil.

The contradiction with **Wataniyat** (Part 3, ch. 25) is then philosophically devastating: the same word *watan* (homeland) that Iqbal used devotionally for Hindustan becomes, in Wataniyat, the name for the "greatest idol" of modernity — "Of all these newer gods, the greatest is the Nation; the robe it wears is Faith's own final desecration." By Part 3 he redefines the concept entirely: "Your homeland is Islam, you serve the Prophet's will" — territory is mere statecraft, not belonging.
